body: Hi @giswqs, I think it caused by the tile `104173-57771-17.jpg` doesn't exist in Mapbox imagery, but it was created while running `label-maker images`. The fast way to solve this problem is just `rm Vietnam_building/tiles/104173-57771-17.jpg` and rerun `label-maker package --dest Vietnam_building --config Vietnam.json`. Hope that would solve the issue.

Thanks your tips @Geoyi ! After I removed the following two images, which appeared to be empty images, the `label-maker package` ran successfully, although the 'skipping' warnings still exist. 

Vietnam_building/tiles/104173-57771-17.jpg
Vietnam_building/tiles/104172-57734-17.jpg
@Geoyi, @drewbo, should we add a check for empty images?

yes, @wronk, but they are not empty images actually, they either don't exist in the zoom level or corrupted while they were downloading. I could not completely figure it out yet how that happened, how can we improve this part @drewbo?

We have a [check in the `package` script](https://github.com/developmentseed/label-maker/blob/master/label_maker/package.py#L62) to ensure the image file is there but we should probably catch the similar error of the file not loading with `Image.open` as well (either `OSError` like shown above or `IOError`)

I just tested the Vietnam example on another computer. The `label-maker package` ran successfully without the errors shown above. So I think @Geoyi is probably right about the error source - some image files might be corrupted while downloading.
Can confirm that I also got this error (`OSError: cannot identify image file`). Image file technically exists, but looks corrupted and can't be opened. Re-downloading images fixed the issue.
